<span class="case-label">Personal Project · Open Data · Electoral Analysis</span>
<h1>VoteView Brasil</h1>
<p class="subtitle">Segmentation and abstention modeling for Pernambuco campaign teams — from raw TSE data to deployable insights.</p>

<div class="meta">
  <div class="meta-item">
    <div class="meta-key">Role</div>
    <div class="meta-val">Solo · Data Science + Full-Stack</div>
  </div>
  <div class="meta-item">
    <div class="meta-key">Stack</div>
    <div class="meta-val">Python · scikit-learn · statsmodels · pandas · React · Supabase</div>
  </div>
  <div class="meta-item">
    <div class="meta-key">Data</div>
    <div class="meta-val">TSE + IBGE · 185 municipalities · 60,172 sections · 3 election cycles</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="tldr">
  <div class="tldr-label">TL;DR</div>
  <p>TSE publishes complete electoral results for every section in Brazil. IBGE publishes demographic data for every municipality. Neither is usable for campaign strategy out of the box. I built the ETL to join them, ran hypothesis-driven clustering to identify five distinct municipal profiles across three election cycles, then fitted OLS regression models explaining 54% of abstention variance. The main finding: elderly population share is the strongest predictor of abstention, and education's mobilizing effect is significantly stronger in federal elections than municipal ones — a distinction most campaign models miss by treating election types as equivalent.</p>
</div>

<div class="section">
  <span class="section-num">01</span>
  <h2>The Challenge</h2>
  <p>Campaign resource allocation depends on understanding which municipalities are persuadable, which are high-turnout, and which abstention patterns are structurally fixed vs. contingent on election type. TSE data is public and granular — vote totals per candidate, per section, per municipality, across three election cycles. But the raw CSVs use proprietary identifier codes that don't match IBGE's geographic schema, field names change between years, and there's no ready-made bridge between electoral behavior and demographic context.</p>
  <p>The analytical question was: can you build a reliable segmentation of Pernambuco's 185 municipalities that is meaningful for campaign targeting — and can you model which demographic variables actually drive abstention, controlling for election type?</p>
</div>

<div class="section">
  <span class="section-num">02</span>
  <h2>Architecture</h2>
  <p>The pipeline separates data infrastructure from analysis. The ETL loads and normalizes TSE and IBGE data into Supabase. The analysis notebooks pull from Supabase and progress in three stages: exploratory hypothesis testing, unsupervised municipal segmentation, and OLS regression modeling. The React frontend surfaces the segmentation and comparative analysis for campaign teams.</p>

